series.defining_characteristics: Available in clad and 40% silver versions. The reverse features the Apollo 11 moon landing mission insignia.
Copper-nickel (1859-1864), Bronze (1864-1909). 1877 is key date with lowest mintage. 1908-S and 1909-S are scarce.
Unique incuse (recessed) design - the only regular-issue US coins with incuse design. Controversial when introduced but now highly prized by collectors.
First modern gold bullion coin. 22K gold (91.67%) with copper alloy. Available in 1 oz, 1/2 oz, 1/4 oz, 1/10 oz sizes. No face value - traded on gold content.
.999 fine silver. Introduced in 2017 for 50th anniversary of original gold Krugerrand. 1 oz size.
100% copper. Early American coinage featuring Liberty wearing Phrygian cap. Weight reduced from 13.48g to 10.89g in 1795. Very rare and valuable.
The Liberty Head (Coronet) design was used for the $2.50 gold piece from 1840-1907. Earlier types (1796-1839) have different designs.
1943 cents were struck in zinc-coated steel due to WWII copper shortage. VDB initials on 1909 reverse are highly collectible.
90% silver. Designed by Adolph A. Weinman. 1916-D is legendary key date (264,000 mintage). Full Bands designation for sharp strike.
Catch-all for 1986+ commemorative gold coins ($5, $10) until individual series defined. Includes all modern gold commemorative programs from Statue of Liberty (1986) to present.
Catch-all for 1982+ commemorative half dollars until individual series defined. Includes all modern clad half dollar commemorative programs.
Catch-all for 1982+ commemorative silver dollars until individual series defined. Includes all modern commemorative dollar programs from Washington 250th Anniversary (1982) to present.
90% silver (1946-1964), Clad (1965-present). Silver proofs available 1992-present. Designed by John R. Sinnock.
Distinctive golden color from manganese brass composition. Continued as Native American $1 series from 2009 with changing reverses.
Multiple design variations: No Stars (1837-1838), Stars (1838-1860), Legend (1860-1891).
